{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657552","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657552"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:30:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:30:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20573"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20573","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20573"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13450"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93688"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13450"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20573"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76898"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"4914"},{"type":"tags","id":"11722"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12797"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32111"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32112"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/93688"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EFibromuscular intimal hyperplasia is a pathological process characterised by proliferation of smooth muscle cells and deposition of extracellular matrix in the intimal layer of muscular arteries. This process leads to luminal narrowing and can significantly compromise blood flow.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following clinical settings is most commonly associated with fibromuscular intimal hyperplasia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Primary hypertension","Post-angioplasty vascular remodelling","Venous thromboembolism","Diabetic microangiopathy","Congenital vascular malformations"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPost-angioplasty vascular remodelling\u003C/strong\u003E is strongly associated with fibromuscular intimal hyperplasia. Following mechanical injury to the vessel wall during procedures such as balloon angioplasty or stent placement, there is a healing response characterised by migration of smooth muscle cells from the media to the intima, proliferation of these cells, and deposition of extracellular matrix. This process can lead to in-stent restenosis, which is a major limitation of interventional procedures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E can lead to vascular remodelling, but this typically involves medial hypertrophy rather than intimal hyperplasia as the predominant change.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVenous thromboembolism\u003C/strong\u003E involves thrombus formation in veins rather than arterial intimal hyperplasia.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic microangiopathy\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects capillaries and arterioles rather than muscular arteries, and involves basement membrane thickening rather than intimal hyperplasia.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongenital vascular malformations\u003C/strong\u003E involve abnormal development of blood vessels during embryogenesis and are not primarily characterised by intimal hyperplasia.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important clinical settings where fibromuscular intimal hyperplasia occurs include solid organ transplant vasculopathy (a form of chronic rejection) and healed arteritis. In both cases, inflammation drives the proliferative response in the intimal layer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fibromuscular intimal hyperplasia is a pathological process characterised by proliferation of smooth muscle cells and extracellular matrix in the intimal layer of muscular arteries.","Fibromuscular intimal hyperplasia can be triggered by inflammatory processes or mechanical injury to the vessel wall.","Fibromuscular intimal hyperplasia is a significant cause of vascular stenosis in specific clinical settings including transplant vasculopathy and post-angioplasty restenosis."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 11; page 493"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76898"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20573"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76898"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-22T08:33:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-22T08:34:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13450"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93688"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4914"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Blood vessels","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-15T20:38:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-15T20:38:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11722"},"attributes":{"emo